      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A specific military innovation—the adoption of the Naue II slashing sword and new infantry tactics by 'barbarian' mercenaries—allowed these groups to overwhelm the chariot-based armies of the palaces, leading to a rapid and violent military collapse.\", \"mechanism\": \"The palatial states relied on elite chariot warriors. Peripheral or mercenary groups, equipped with cheap, mass-produced Naue II swords and javelins, developed effective swarm tactics that neutralized chariot charges. These groups, initially hired as mercenaries, turned on their employers, sacking the poorly defended palatial centers in a short, violent wave.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"The Naue II sword was not in widespread use until after the palatial destructions.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The destruction layers show evidence of prolonged sieges and widespread burning from external attack.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian records describe the Sea Peoples as fighting primarily as chariot-based aristocracies.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This conjecture is more atypical as it focuses narrowly on a military-technological shift and limits its scope to the Aegean and Anatolia, where the Naue II sword was prevalent. It explains the survival of Egypt through their successful adaptation and defeat of these new infantry tactics, as recorded at Medinet Habu.\"}",
